In the two months since the presidential election, as it=E2=80=99s
become apparent to an already disillusioned Washington Post staff that Will=
 Lewis=E2=80=99s grand plan for pulling the the paper out of its extended m=
alaise amounts to a convoluted newsroom restructuring led by the existing m=
asthead, several of the company=E2=80=99s most notable journalists have dec=
ided that it=E2=80=99s finally time to consider their options. The coup de =
gr=C3=A2ce for these folks=E2=80=94after years of diminished influence, enn=
ui, and recurring bouts of antipathy toward Lewis,
himself=E2=80=94appears to have been the surprise news that their beloved c=
olleague Matea Gold would be decamping to The New York Times upon being pas=
sed over for the top editor job.

=C2=A0

Could it have really been a surprise that Lewis and Jeff Bezos would view a=
 largely innovation-lite, lifer-ish newsroom executive as an also-ran stalk=
ing horse in their search? Gold,
who lined up a lesser job at the Times, represented an umbilical link to th=
e past, a comforting figure amid a slowly unfolding and darkening regime ch=
ange=E2=80=94all reasons she would never have gotten the job in the first p=
lace. (Indeed, Lewis didn=E2=80=99t even present a counteroffer to keep her=
 from going to the Times.) But for many in the newsroom, her departure was =
of seismic significance. And the camel=E2=80=99s back had already been pile=
d high with straw.

=C2=A0

Anyway, last week, I reported that Lewis had quietly decided to appoint act=
ing executive editor Matt Murray to that position permanently, possibly for=
 lack of any better option. (The muted communication of the announcement is=
 an apt metaphor for the enthusiasm generated by the appointment.) Even tho=
ugh these are all, ostensibly, business decisions rendered to rescue a comp=
any hemorrhaging nearly $100 million per year, the
Matt-over-Matea news was received rather personally by many in the building=
=2E =E2=80=9CPeople are very upset abou=
t Matea,=E2=80=9D one source told me t=
he other day, =E2=80=9CAnd then you ruined everyone=E2=80=99s weekend with =
the Murray news.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

I am now reliably told that well-known political reporters including Josh D=
awsey, Ashley Parker, Tyler Pager, Michael Scherer, and several
others are either mulling a transfer or have already decided to exit. Dawse=
y, for instance, is said to be entertaining multiple offers while on book l=
eave=E2=80=94a notably contemplative choreography befitting the modern Post=
=2E Parker is in late-stage negotiation=
s with The Atlantic. Historically, the=
se reporters have stayed loyal to the Post due to their faith in the storie=
d institution=E2=80=94and, for a time, its centibillionaire owner=E2=80=94a=
nd the benefits of
being a bigger fish in a smaller and less cutthroat pond. Now, many seem to=
 fear the consequences of staying on too long, particularly amid the specte=
r of yet another round of what I=E2=80=99m told will be severe layoffs acro=
ss the company in the year ahead.

